%BOM---------------------
Date:6/3/2009 12:00:29 AM
From:Paul Senior
I've made very few sales. Trimmed some positions where I got tired of losses,
and sold out of some penny stocks where I couldn't see any hope of improvement.
Some of these stocks weren't penny stocks when I bought them :>(

I am now in a position where I didn't want to be, which is to be still having
funds to invest even after the market has moved up -- moved up faster than I
have been willing to make buy commitments. The ole "what do I do now" problem,
which problem I believed would affect others, but not me. Ha.

This past year's downturn has adversely affected all of the many sectors in
which I have been diversified.
I am now considering one new sector in which I've not had a participation and
that is short-selling. While this isn't a "short term strategy to book these
gains w/o giving away your under valued prospects", had I at least had and kept
a few shorts out, that might have somewhat mitigated my poor performance the
past eight months. I am considering keeping a few short positions as a
strategy. That would be a tactic for the portfolio. I have started recently
with a couple of stocks.

As far as "some short term strategy to book these gains w/o giving away your
under valued prospects," I have nothing to offer. My intent is fixed: I want to
buy stocks when they look undervalued and sell them only when they approach
fair value or overvalue. Always and only. Yet I waver. Which happens. Like
always when a buy is made on day one and by day three the the stock is up like
25% or more--- what to do, what to do. -g- A nice problem.

As a corollary, something else I don't consciously do is to balance a portfolio
by trimming an outsize position after a rise. I'd rather have an unbalanced
portfolio with a stock that's rising. Too hard for me to find great stocks, and
when I have enough of one (to where it makes a significant difference to the
portfolio), I want to keep it.

Of course, all jmo, and I've been wrong many, many times.
=======================
=======================
To protect gains I suppose the typical answer might be to put trailing stops
on. Something I've never done.
