From:Paul Senior
For now, I'm just looking at shorting a few individual stocks; I've not
considered sector shorts as with an ETF. I don't want to short an ETF in a
sector in which I hold individual stocks -- that seems like betting against
myself. Also since I'm pretty diversified, I don't know of any sector ETF that
I don't have positions in.

I am basically looking to learn to hedge using shorts. Finding and
experimenting with some stocks where if the stock market goes up, the shorted
stock -- for whatever reason, e.g. it's overvalued, it's beta is low (it's a
dullard) -- it perhaps won't go up as much as my longs. And if my stocks
decline in a down market, and the shorted stock drops too, at least I will have
a very little something that is green.

I'm going to bet on Berkshire as one such stock. Otoh, while I believe
something like Chipotle http://finance.yahoo.com/q?s=CMG is way overvalued, we
see that that one can rally more than the market in good days (It's up right
now even with today's very down market.), and so I'm not too willing to really
consider shorting something overvalued like that as a hedge.
